\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0

\f1\fs32 \cf7 \cb5 Gaps still open\cb1 \
\pard\pardeftab720\sa240\partightenfactor0

\f0\fs26 \cf7 \cb5 1. A Fee-Value Estimator (the master ranker)\cb1 \uc0\u8232 \cb5 Right now every tool produces signals, but nothing ranks them by\'a0expected \'a3: probability of winning \'d7 likely salary \'d7 fee % \uc0\u8722  cost-to-serve. Two signals rated "HIGH severity" aren't equal if one is a \'a330k fee and the other is a \'a3120k fee. Without this, Sara's attention gets spent on the loudest signal, not the most lucrative one. This should be the master ranker sitting across the whole digest.\cb1 \
\cb5 2. Historical-Desk Integration (JobAdder import)\cb1 \uc0\u8232 \cb5 Every external signal is context-free until it's cross-referenced with Sara's own history: every past placement, every lapsed conversation, every fee she charged, every PSL position, every candidate she's submitted before. A "Barclays CEO departure" signal is very different if she placed 3 roles there in 2021\'9623 vs if she's never worked with them. I've been designing the system as if the internal data doesn't exist. It does, and it's the single highest-signal input.\cb1 \
\cb5 3. PSL / Framework Tracker\cb1 \uc0\u8232 \cb5 Signals are useless if VMA can't legally bid. Where is VMA already on PSL? Where are frameworks (CCS, NHS, specific corporates) renewing? Where does Sara need a new relationship before the signal can be actioned? Missing this means the digest will keep surfacing unactionable "hot briefs."\cb1 \
\cb5 4. Warm-Path Finder (graph across her whole network)\cb1 \uc0\u8232 \cb5 For every "call this person today", the tool should automatically surface the warmest intro path through her placed candidates, mutual connections, IoIC/CIPR membership overlap, alumni networks, and her colleagues' networks. I mentioned "warm path" inside the Decision-Maker Dossier but didn't make it a\'a0systematic graph tool\'a0running across every suggested call. Warm intros convert 3\'965\'d7 cold ones. Missing this is missing money.\cb1 \
\cb5 5. Timing Engine (corporate cycle layer)\cb1 \uc0\u8232 \cb5 Results windows, board meeting dates, FY starts, budget approval cycles, pre-Christmas freeze, January unlock. Calling a CHRO 48 hours\'a0
\f2\i post
\f0\i0 -results converts materially better than 48 hours\'a0
\f2\i pre
\f0\i0 -. None of the tools currently know "call now vs call in 3 weeks." Adding a timing layer to the ranker moves conversion rates without doing any more scanning.\cb1 \
\cb5 6. Placement-Risk Scorer (clawback protector)\cb1 \uc0\u8232 \cb5 Every placement carries a 3\'966 month guarantee. A failed placement = fee clawed back = negative commission. A scorer that predicts placement stickiness (candidate's tenure pattern, client's historical churn, role-scope mismatch flags, cultural red flags)\'a0protects\'a0commission as directly as landing a new placement creates it. In \'a3 terms, avoiding one clawback = winning one new placement. The system currently has no view on this.\cb1 \
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0

