\cf2 \cb3 The recruiter's intelligence engine, built on Claude Code Opus 4.7\
The short answer is yes \'97 Claude Code Opus 4.7 can build this tool, and with the right signal stack it is plausibly worth one to three extra placements a year to Sara Tehrani, which pays for itself roughly forty times over. The capability that matters most \'97 Anthropic's Cloud Routines, shipped on 14 April 2026 \'97 turns Claude Code from a desk-side assistant into a scheduled, cloud-hosted agent that can run headless every morning before Sara opens her laptop. What it cannot do alone is scrape LinkedIn at scale legally; that problem is solved by licensing one data broker and leaning on three under-exploited public UK data sources (Companies House Streaming, HR1 redundancy filings, internal-comms-platform vendor customer pages) that almost no competitor systematically mines. The rest of this report establishes what the morning brief should contain, why, and how to construct it.\
\
Sara's commercial shape dictates the design. A \'a3400k gross-profit target at a \'a314.3k average fee implies around 28 successful placements; her plan to take interims from zero to 24 means the tool must be twin-tracked between permanent BD and interim availability, not a single pipeline. Seventy per cent of her work is self-generated, so the brief's job is to manufacture high-quality BD triggers she would otherwise miss, not to replicate what already sits in the VMA CRM. Her 100 lapsed contacts and 20\'9625 key accounts create a natural "watchlist" architecture; this is the spine around which the intelligence engine is assembled.\
\
