What the data actually predicts: the BD signal universe\
The honest finding from primary research is that the recruitment-tech industry has over-promised on "predictive" signals. Almost every tool that claims to predict moves is running periodic re-scrapes and detecting change after it has happened, typically a week or two later (hireEZ, SeekOut, Gem, Findem, Juicebox). The genuinely predictive signals for "this company is about to hire a senior comms leader" are fewer than the usual industry lists suggest, but those that do predict are substantially under-exploited.\
\
Tier 1 \'97 highest predictive value, low competitive crowding, build first:\
\
The single most valuable under-used source is the Companies House Streaming API (stream.companieshouse.gov.uk). It is free, real-time, push-based, and gives you \
Service\
 AP01 (new officer) and TM01 (terminating appointment) events within minutes of filing for all five million UK companies. \
GlobalDatabase\
 Harvard Business School research (Sadun, Impink, Prat, 2024) shows employee-facing communication collapses in the first three to five months after a CEO transition, then rebounds roughly 20% above baseline as the new chief executive rolls out a strategy narrative. Months three to five post-CEO change is the sweet-spot pitch window; almost no UK comms recruiter systematically filters the officer stream for CEO, CHRO, CPO and Managing Director churn. For Sara, this is the most durable source of differentiated BD leads.\
\
Equal in value are HR1 collective redundancy filings. Under the Trade Union and Labour Relations (Consolidation) Act 1992, any UK employer proposing 20 or more redundancies must file HR1 with the Insolvency Service. \
Royal College of Nursing\
DavidsonMorris\
