UK comms hiring cycles and competitor context: what Sara should see daily\
Comms hiring in the UK has a pronounced seasonal rhythm that the brief's weighting logic should respect. Q1 (January\'96March) is the heaviest window: January's "new year new job" resignations combine with budget unlocks and the March bonus cycle in financial services and professional services. Q2 peaks in AGM season (May\'96June), which drives investor-relations and corporate-affairs churn \'97 plus the CIPR Excellence Awards and IoIC's Festival of Internal Communication both hit in June, creating high-density networking moments that accelerate moves. Q3 (July\'96August) is the summer lull, re-accelerating sharply in September as deferred bonus cycles trigger resignations. Q4 (October\'96November) is the second-heaviest permanent window, with December typically dead except for crisis and interim work.\
\
Sector-specific overlays matter too. Financial services hires in Feb\'96April post-results and in July\'96August for interims; SMCR is a perennial hiring driver. Pharma's cycle runs on MHRA/EMA product approvals and the ABPI Code Chapter 26 constraints on promotional comms. Energy and utilities track Ofgem price-cap cycles. Tech scale-ups hit a predictable comms-hiring moment at Series C (first Head of Comms) and Series D / pre-IPO (VP or Chief). Public sector hiring moves through the GCS framework at SCS Paybands 1 and 2 (\'a376k\'96\'a3162k), much slower and more structured.\
\
On the rival-intelligence question, Sara's direct competitors fall into clear segments. Watson Helsby owns C-suite FTSE 100 corporate affairs (Nick Helsby's annual Group Director survey is the canonical benchmark). Ellwood Atfield \'97 now 100% employee-owned since November 2023 \'97 owns senior corporate affairs, policy and membership bodies. The Works Search dominates financial-comms agencies (Brunswick, FGS, Teneo, H/Advisors) and FTSE corporate comms via its Platinum retained service. Hanson Search is the strongest global-reach boutique with an interim arm via The Work Crowd. BIE Executive and Green Park compete in interim and transformation, with Green Park particularly strong on DEI-led mandates and the public and third sectors. Reuben Sinclair (Official Talent Partner to CIPR and PRCA), 3Search and Major Players compete at agency and mid-market levels. CommsSearch & Selection (Max Forsyth) is a small but credible direct competitor at CCO level.\
\
The daily intelligence Sara genuinely needs on this list is narrower than one might assume: placements announced by rival firms (reveals which incumbents have just been replaced \'97 those incumbents are now candidates); consultant lateral moves (consultants carry live mandates and candidate books); rival job adverts over six weeks old (signals struggling search \'97 opportunity to pitch a shadow search); new marketing and salary reports (requires a VMA response narrative); and Companies House filing events at rival firms (revenue shape, structural changes).\
\
One naming point worth flagging from the research: Sapience Communications is a PR consultancy, not a recruiter (Companies House 07527730, SIC 82990), so it is a competitor to Sara's clients rather than to VMA. "Kin Partnership" could not be definitively identified as a distinct UK comms recruiter; the closest match is Kin Collective Recruitment Ltd. Both should be demoted in the rival-watchlist.\
