What the morning brief should actually look like\
The brief must work at three reading speeds simultaneously: a 30-second scan from Sara's phone while her kettle boils, a 3-minute triage before her 09:00, and a 30-minute deep read during her Friday planning block. The design that delivers all three is BLUF-structured HTML with progressive disclosure, not a traditional "digest" layout.\
\
The subject line carries three things: the date, a count of priority-one items, and a single stand-out headline (example: "Brief 21 Apr \'97 3 P1 leads \'97 Lloyds CHRO out, Diageo hires first Head of IC"). Sara can clear non-actionable days from the preview pane without opening.\
\
The opening block is a "30-second summary" \'97 three or at most four numbered priority-one items, each a single sentence naming the company or candidate, the signal, and the recommended next action. Every other item in the brief lives below this fold.\
\
Underneath sits three tabbed or headed sections in fixed order: Opportunities (BD leads, ranked by signal-stack score), Movers (candidates showing imminent-move signals, with interim availability flagged separately for Sara's zero-to-24 target), and Context (rival activity, trade press digest, awards cycle, sector news \'97 all one-liners with links). Each Opportunity entry is a collapsible card containing: the company name and size, the composite signal stack with dates, the likely role, a probability score with one sentence of rationale, three to five pre-drafted opening-line angles Sara can paraphrase (not send automatically), the name and LinkedIn URL of the likely hiring manager, and a one-click link to either the ATS record (if known) or a pre-drafted Bullhorn creation payload. Each Movers entry is similar but flipped: candidate, signals, likely availability date, current and past employers, a shortlist of three to five employers where they would fit Sara's live briefs, and a pre-drafted reach-out angle.\
\
The three-minute read adds a "Deltas" section showing what changed since yesterday's brief \'97 a new signal on an existing lead, a disappeared signal (employer filled the vacancy elsewhere \'97 deprioritise), or a candidate moving from "watching" to "imminent". This is the bit Claude Code's persistent memory enables and that no SaaS tool delivers.\
\
The thirty-minute read, for Friday planning, is a "Key accounts" panel iterating over Sara's 20\'9625 key accounts and her 100 lapsed contacts one by one: for each, the most recent signal (if any), a compact timeline of last-90-day activity, and a flagged recommendation ("no contact 147 days, last role placed Dec 2024, three signals in last month \'97 reactivate this week"). This is the single highest-leverage section for Sara's 70% self-generated business.\
\
A small economics footer runs on each card: for BD leads, a rough estimated fee if converted (using role seniority and Sara's 20% average); for candidates, an estimated market rate. Over a month the footer aggregates into a "pipeline value in the brief this month" number, giving Sara a running sense of whether the tool is pulling its weight. Her realistic target \'97 three to five genuine placement conversations initiated per week from the brief \'97 is a credible yield given the signal stack.\
\
Length target: the HTML email should comfortably sit under 40kB (roughly 6\'968 screens on mobile) by keeping the top three priority-one items above the fold and everything else collapsible. Claude Code can generate the HTML directly in the final sub-agent step; a React Email template via Resend is the cleanest implementation.\
\
Validating the six prior gaps: what Claude can genuinely do\
The prior session flagged six gaps. Against the research, here is an honest scoring.\
\
(a) Shortlist pre-building \'97 strongly validated. This is where Claude Code's advantage is largest. A daily maintained shortlist per key account, continuously updated as signals shift, allows Sara to respond to a live brief in hours rather than days; on a fast-moving retained mandate this is the difference between winning and not pitching. The persistent-memory layer (state/shortlists_by_account.json plus the Managed Agents Memory Store) makes this technically straightforward.\
\
(b) Exclusivity and retained conversion \'97 partially validated. Sara's target of converting two mandates to retained search in H1 is real, but the lever is mostly interpersonal and commercial, not informational. What the tool can do is manufacture the conditions for retained conversion: (i) surfacing BD signals that indicate confidential, time-sensitive or off-market searches (the situations in which clients agree to retained); (ii) building the pre-shortlist that lets Sara walk into a pitch with candidate evidence in hand, which is the strongest argument for retained fees; (iii) modelling the cost-of-vacancy to the client (see (c)). It cannot replace the sales conversation.\
\
(c) Client ROI modelling \'97 strongly validated. Claude Code with long context can pull a client's annual report, calculate a rough EBITDA-per-employee, estimate the cost of a senior comms vacancy (typically 1\'963\'d7 the role's annual salary for senior operational roles, substantially more for roles with high stakeholder-management content), and produce a one-page ROI case on demand. This is pitch-deck-quality analysis that would otherwise require an analyst half-day.\
\
(d) Outcome-trained ranking \'97 validated but needs a feedback loop. The tool will not improve without Sara's feedback. The design includes a /rate slash command: when Sara replies to the brief with a quick "used", "irrelevant" or "already placed", the orchestrator updates the memory store and re-weights signal classes accordingly. After six months this closes the loop that no generalist SaaS tool can, because the weights become specific to Sara's desk rather than to a generic sourcing model.\
\
(e) Referral-chain tracking through placed candidates' careers \'97 strongly validated and novel. This is one of the tool's most durable advantages. Every candidate Sara has ever placed becomes a continuous open-record watch: a placed Head of IC who moves to a new company two years later is simultaneously a warm-intro BD lead at the new employer and a backfill candidate opportunity at the old employer \'97 and the warm-intro rate at the new employer is an order of magnitude higher than cold BD. No competitor tool does this systematically, and it compounds: each additional placement enlarges Sara's referral graph.\
\
(f) Fee-negotiation support at the moment of truth \'97 validated as a pull-demand feature rather than a daily push. Claude Code can generate a negotiation brief on demand \'97 a client's recent placements and the fees paid (where public), their funding position, their cost-of-vacancy estimate, the uniqueness of the candidate profile against the UK pool, and comparable recent placements \'97 in minutes. This lives as a slash command Sara invokes when a fee conversation is imminent, not as part of the morning brief.\
\
One additional gap the research surfaced that was not in the original six: interim availability forecasting. Given Sara's zero-to-24 interim target, the Companies-House-plus-LinkedIn contract-end prediction is effectively its own pipeline, and the brief should treat it as a separate swim-lane rather than folding it into general candidate intelligence.\
\
Risks, limits and what this tool will not do\
The tool's legitimacy rests on keeping four disciplines. First, no direct LinkedIn scraping \'97 only licensed Bright Data or Coresignal datasets, plus Sara's own Sales Navigator Recruiter \'97 or Sara inherits Proxycurl's legal risk. Second, a live Legitimate Interests Assessment and Data Protection Impact Assessment per the ICO's March 2026 guidance, refreshed annually, with an explicit retention policy capping candidate-signal data at six months for non-engaged profiles. Third, a standing Article 14 disclosure on VMA's website explaining the sources and processing, so first contact with any candidate is compliant. Fourth, no automated outbound \'97 the tool is a pure intelligence engine, exactly as the brief specified, which neatly sidesteps the hardest part of the compliance envelope.\
\
There are four operational risks worth naming. Cloud Routines are a research preview; Anthropic may change the pricing or constraints. The new Opus 4.7 tokeniser can inflate token counts by up to 35% over identical text input under the old tokeniser, so monthly costs should be benchmarked against real runs, not list prices (finout.io/blog/claude-opus-4.7-pricing). LinkedIn's anti-scraping posture may tighten further and force a broker change mid-year. And prompt-injection attacks via scraped content are a genuine risk for any agent that ingests HTML; Anthropic's guidance is never to combine untrusted content with sensitive credentials in the same context, which the sub-agent architecture enforces by design but the recruiter should not override.\
\
What this tool explicitly will not do, and should not try: it will not send outbound messages, will not generate CVs, will not score candidates in a way that causes an Article 22 automated-decision problem under UK GDPR, will not cold-scrape LinkedIn, and will not attempt to guess at protected characteristics. Sara remains the human layer for every piece of execution, which is both the correct ethical posture and the commercial design.\
\
The definitive verdict\
A specialist UK IC/Corp Comms recruiter at Sara's scale has, in April 2026, a genuinely unusual technology moment: the model (Opus 4.7 with one-million-token context and no premium), the runtime (Cloud Routines), the orchestration layer (sub-agents and MCP), and the data universe (Companies House Streaming, HR1, RNS, IC-platform vendor pages, licensed LinkedIn) have all matured within roughly twelve months of each other. Three of the highest-value signals \'97 officer-change streaming, HR1 redundancy filings, and IC-platform customer stories \'97 are essentially unwatched by her direct competitors, which means a well-built brief offers a measurable BD edge rather than parity.\
\
The realistic yield, assuming disciplined daily engagement, is one to three placements per year that Sara would otherwise have missed. At her \'a314.3k average fee that is \'a314,300 to \'a342,900 of additional revenue, against a tool stack cost of roughly \'a33,000\'96\'a36,000 per year \'97 a return multiple of between five and fourteen. More importantly for her retained-search ambition, the shortlist-pre-building and client-ROI-modelling capabilities give her a qualitatively different pitch posture than a competitor relying on Bullhorn and LinkedIn alone.\
\
The morning brief at its best is a short, priority-ranked, HTML-delivered artefact that reads in 30 seconds, gives Sara five to twelve genuinely actionable leads per day, pre-drafts the angles she can paraphrase, and keeps a compounding record of her desk's learning. Claude Code Opus 4.7, configured as described, can build it \'97 not as a thought-experiment, but as a production system the research-preview tooling now supports, at a cost and risk profile that a \'a3400k-target specialist recruiter can justify on the first placement the tool generates.\
