re-write this for someone who doesnt work in recruitment so i can understandShow more02:15Let me do a clean diff between the original 11+6 plan and what the research actually surfaced as valuable. I'll split it into three buckets: things the plan had that the research validated, things the plan was missing entirely, and things the plan had that the research suggests are weaker than you think.\
What the research added that your plan does not currently have\
The biggest miss is Companies House Streaming API as a real-time source. Your Company Radar describes scanning for "leadership departures" \'97 the research makes the specific point that UK companies file officer changes (new directors, terminating directors) to Companies House within days of the event, and Companies House publishes a free push-based stream of every filing across all five million UK companies in near real time. CEO, CHRO, CPO and MD changes filtered from that stream beat PRWeek's "Movers and Shakers" reporting by weeks and sometimes months. No comms recruiter in the UK systematically watches this. Your plan treats leadership departure as one of many signals; the research says it should be its own pillar because it's the single highest-value under-exploited signal in the UK comms market, and because the Harvard research on CEO transitions pinpoints months three to five after a CEO change as the sweet-spot pitch window. Your plan doesn't reference this timing window at all.\
The second miss is HR1 redundancy filings. Under UK law, any employer proposing 20+ redundancies must file Form HR1 with the Insolvency Service approximately four to six weeks before the public announcement. Aggregate weekly data is published by ONS; named-employer data is routinely obtained via FOI requests (the BBC and Guardian do this quarterly). Restructuring almost always generates a Change Communications Director hire \'97 typically interim at \'a3800-\'a31,200/day converting to permanent at \'a390-130k. This is directly aimed at Sara's zero-to-24 interim target and it's a month-ahead signal. Your plan captures "restructuring announcements" as a Company Radar signal, but it's watching for the public announcement, which is the moment every other recruiter sees it too. HR1 filings are the upstream signal, and the research says in the current April 2026 market \'97 where redundancies and restructuring are "the main drivers" of hiring activity \'97 this is arguably the single most valuable BD pillar for the next 12 months.\
The third miss is internal-comms platform vendor customer pages. Staffbase, Poppulo and Firstup publish case studies of new customer wins on their websites. A \'a3100k+ platform purchase almost always presupposes either an existing Head of Internal Comms to sponsor it, or a new one to be hired to deploy it. When a UK company appears as a new Staffbase customer and has no visible Head of IC on LinkedIn, the probability of a hire inside 90 days is materially elevated. This signal is essentially invisible to every competitor and trivially scrapeable. Your plan has no equivalent. This is pure alpha that costs almost nothing to extract.\
The fourth miss is signal stacking as the core ranking logic. Your plan lists 11 tools as if each produces standalone alerts. The research argues that no single signal has better than ~30% precision for predicting a specific comms hire, but stacking two or three independent signals (for example: HR1 filing + no visible Head of IC + Staffbase customer story + CHRO change six months ago) pushes compound probability above 70%. This is the cross-referencing work Claude Code does better than any SaaS product, because it holds all the streams in one reasoning context. Your Fee-Value Estimator gap is the right instinct but describes it as a probability multiplier rather than the signal-stacking engine it actually needs to be. The distinction matters: a multiplier ranks; a stacking engine filters out 80% of single-signal noise before ranking even runs.\
The fifth miss is interim contract-end-date prediction via Companies House cross-reference. This is the specific mechanic that makes the Interim Bench Tracker actually work. Most interim communicators run personal service companies whose directorships, PSC records and filing histories are fully public on Companies House. Combined with LinkedIn current-role start dates and typical 6/9/12-month contract lengths, a T-minus-eight-weeks "about to be available" flag produces interim leads weeks before the competition sees them. Your Interim Bench Tracker describes the output but not the mechanism. The mechanism is the defensible piece.\
The sixth miss is incumbent-to-candidate flip logic. When any signal fires on a senior comms leader departing a company, the orchestrator should automatically flag that person both as a new BD lead (their old employer now has a vacancy) and a new candidate lead (they are likely about to be available, often in transit between roles). Your Company Radar and Openness Radar are listed as separate tools; the research says they need to share a memory store so a single departure event populates both sides of the desk simultaneously.\
The seventh miss is an Article 14 / UK GDPR legitimate-interests compliance layer. The ICO's March 2026 guidance, reflecting the Data (Use and Access) Act 2025, explicitly expects a documented Legitimate Interests Assessment and a Data Protection Impact Assessment before deploying an AI-driven recruitment intelligence tool. Article 14 imposes a duty to inform candidates within one month if their data was collected from a source other than themselves. Your plan has no compliance layer. This is not optional and it's also a defensive moat \'97 a compliant tool is legally sellable as a VMA-wide asset; a non-compliant one is a liability that gets shut down on first ICO complaint.\
What the plan includes that the research suggests is weaker than it looks\
Your Glassdoor trajectory signal \'97 the academic evidence links Glassdoor trends to share returns and CEO turnover, not directly to comms hires. It's fine as an enrichment data point but shouldn't be a trigger.\
Your Annual report stakeholder-language-shift signal \'97 too lagging and too noisy relative to the signals above. The research suggests demoting it to enrichment.\
Your awards-tracking as a candidate move signal \'97 the research flagged this as counter-intuitively a negative indicator. Employers use awards to justify retention bonuses, locking winners in for 6-12 months. Your Openness Radar should either exclude awards or use them as a don't-call-yet flag.\
Your exec-education enrolments as a move signal \'97 40-60% are employer-sponsored per VMA's own research. Useful as context, not as a trigger.\
Your posting-frequency NLP analysis of "tone becoming more reflective" \'97 unreliable at scale, drowned by LinkedIn's corporate writing conventions.\
Your Company Radar's "earnings-call language shifts" \'97 beloved of quant hedge funds but too noisy for a specific comms-hire trigger. Keep the data, don't alert on it.\
What the research confirmed was correctly identified in your plan\
The lapsed-client flag mechanic is correct and important \'97 any signal touching Sara's 100 lapsed contacts should be auto-promoted to the top tier regardless of absolute score. The research reinforces this as watchlist-intersection logic.\
The Placed-Candidate Watch is correctly identified as a referral-chain engine rather than just a double-fee succession tool \'97 every past placement becomes a continuous open-record watch that eventually generates warm-intro BD leads at each new employer they move to.\
The Decision-Maker Dossier is correctly scoped, though the research adds that it should include a cost-of-vacancy ROI calculation the client themselves would find persuasive, which unlocks retained fee conversations.\
The Procurement Mine is correctly listed but the research flags that public-sector framework wins by other companies are actually the higher-value version \'97 a supplier winning a large government contract often hires a public affairs lead within 60 days, and this is visible via the same Contracts Finder and Find a Tender feeds your plan already names.\
The Fee & Rate Benchmark is correctly identified but the research says the pitch-moment negotiation brief (on-demand, invoked by slash command) is the higher-value use of the same underlying data \'97 real-time benchmarks are table-stakes, but a negotiation brief that pulls the specific client's recent placements, funding position, cost-of-vacancy estimate, and comparable placements in minutes is what actually wins fee conversations.\
The Morning Digest is correctly scoped but the research pushes hard on the UX: a 30-second scan needs BLUF structure with three priority-one items above the fold, everything else collapsible, and a running "pipeline value surfaced this month" footer so Sara can see the tool pulling its weight without having to audit it manually.\
The six "gaps to uncap the ceiling" versus the research\
Your Fee-Value Estimator \'97 right instinct, wrong architecture. Should be a signal-stacking engine that filters before it ranks, not a probability multiplier applied to single signals.\
Your Historical-Desk Integration \'97 confirmed, and should use the Managed Agents Memory Store that Anthropic shipped in April 2026 rather than a custom database, which removes the engineering overhead.\
Your PSL / Framework Tracker \'97 confirmed, and the research adds that framework renewal dates themselves are a BD signal worth firing alerts on, not just a filter.\
Your Warm-Path Finder \'97 confirmed and extended. The referral graph from placed candidates is more valuable than IoIC/CIPR overlap or alumni networks, because warm-intro conversion rates from past placements are an order of magnitude higher than cold BD.\
Your Timing Engine \'97 confirmed, but the research adds one specific high-value timing insight: the three-to-five-month post-CEO-change window is the single most actionable timing signal in UK comms hiring and deserves its own alert class.\
Your Placement-Risk Scorer \'97 confirmed, but the research flags this as a pull-demand feature (invoked at offer stage) rather than a continuously-running scorer. Cheaper to build, more useful.\
The plan's single structural weakness\
The plan is organised around tools. The research suggests it should be organised around signal domains that feed into a single orchestrator that does signal-stacking, watchlist intersection, incumbent-to-candidate flip, and referral-chain tracking as cross-cutting logic. You currently have, for example, Company Radar and Openness Radar as separate tools \'97 the research argues they are two views of the same signal store, and separating them into "tools" means you'll build the sharing mechanism badly as an afterthought. The cleanest rebuild is eight parallel ingestion agents (one per signal source) feeding a single reasoning layer that produces one brief with BD and candidate swim-lanes \'97 which is also, not coincidentally, exactly what Claude Code Opus 4.7's sub-agent architecture makes natural to build.\
If you want, I can produce a clean rewritten version of the plan that folds all of this in as a single unified document.so taking the deep research report into account and everything in this chat so far, how would you elicit what the critical tools should be  for the specific goal of: the best possible commission-maximising machine for a recruiter who still does the human execution herself10:51Here's how I'd actually elicit it, rather than guess.\
The reason the original 11+6 list was a mixed bag is that it was generated top-down from "what's theoretically possible" rather than bottom-up from "what does Sara actually do all day, and where does she leak fees." To build the right tool you need to close that gap, and the way you close it is with a structured interrogation of her desk. Not a survey. A diagnostic conversation that each of these questions is designed to force a specific answer out of.\
Start with the money, not the signals. Before a single tool is specified, I'd want Sara to walk through her last 12 months placement by placement \'97 all 20 of them. For each: where did the lead originate (lapsed contact, referral, inbound, cold BD, rival firm spillover), how many days from first contact to brief, how many days from brief to placement, what was the fee, and \'97 most importantly \'97 what would have had to be true for her to have found this lead 30 days earlier than she did. That last question is the one that tells you what the tool needs to do. If 12 of 20 placements came from signals that existed publicly weeks before she knew about them, you have your answer on what to build first.\
Then the inverse: the losses. Every recruiter has a list of briefs they pitched for and lost, or heard about too late, or couldn't respond to in time. I'd want Sara to list the last 30 of those she can remember, and for each one identify who won it and why. This is the darker but more instructive dataset, because it tells you where the competitive edge needs to be sharpest. If she lost eight of thirty to Hanson Search on speed, the tool's priority is speed. If she lost them on candidate depth, the tool's priority is the pre-built shortlist. If she lost them because she never heard about the brief, the tool's priority is signal coverage.\
Then the time audit. I'd ask her to track, across one typical week, how many minutes she spends on each of: reading PRWeek and industry press, scrolling LinkedIn for company news, checking Companies House or regulatory filings, searching her own JobAdder records for context before a call, writing bespoke pitches, briefing prep, benchmarking fees, candidate research, and proactive BD outreach. The tool should be designed to compress the first seven and protect the eighth. If she's currently spending four hours a week on research that Claude can do in fifteen minutes, those four hours become either more BD calls or earlier evenings \'97 both of which have a fee value.\
Then the specific question the earlier report got wrong. I'd ask Sara: "When you win a retained mandate instead of a contingent one, what is the conversation that precedes it?" Because retained conversion is the single highest fee multiplier available to her (\'a330k versus \'a35-7k on the same role) and the research found that the lever is mostly the walk-in-with-evidence posture \'97 arriving at the pitch meeting with three credible names already in mind. The tool needs to know what evidence persuades her specific clients, which means knowing which of her clients have been persuadable in the past and why.\
Then the lapsed-contact question, properly. Her plan names 100 lapsed contacts. I'd want her to segment them: how many are warm enough that a single well-timed call would reopen the relationship versus how many need a legitimate BD pretext? Because for the first group the tool's job is simply to trigger her at the right moment; for the second group the tool needs to manufacture the pretext (a signal at their company, a relevant market insight, a candidate referral they might want). Different tools for different segments, and the 100 is probably split 30/70.\
Then the interim question, which is the biggest lever she has. She went from zero interim placements to a target of 24. I'd ask: "Who are the 50 UK interim IC/Corp Comms professionals you'd want to place if they all rang you tomorrow?" Because a list of 50 names, ranked by contract-end proximity and cross-referenced with Companies House, is a functional interim bench on day one and tells the tool exactly whose contract-end dates and availability signals to watch. Without that list, the tool is scanning the whole UK interim universe and ranking generically. With it, the tool is watching her actual preferred bench.\
Then the competitive question. I'd ask her which three rival recruiters she loses to most often, and for each, what they do better than she does. Not what they do differently \'97 what they do better. Because the tool needs to neutralise those specific advantages. If Hanson wins on global reach, the tool needs to surface international diaspora candidates she'd otherwise miss. If Ellwood Atfield wins on C-suite network depth, the tool needs to build her CCO/Corporate Affairs Director dossier faster than she could manually.\
Then the question almost no one asks a recruiter. I'd ask Sara: "What do you currently know about your market that your rivals don't?" Because whatever that is, it needs to be baked into the tool's reasoning layer \'97 as taxonomy, as target-account logic, as the specific qualitative judgments she makes about sector fit, personality match, and cultural red flags. That knowledge is the moat, not the signal scraping. The signals are commoditisable; the judgement is not. The tool's job is to scale her judgement, not replace it.\
Finally, the cold question. What does a month of receiving this brief and not using it look like for her? Because the single biggest risk with a daily intelligence product isn't that it surfaces the wrong signals \'97 it's that she stops reading it by week three. The design has to pre-empt that. Which means asking her: what format, length, time of day, and feedback mechanism would you actually engage with for 250 mornings a year? If the answer is "a 90-second Slack message with three bullets and a link to the full brief," then the full HTML email I described in the report is the wrong product. The elicitation has to land on the delivery format before the ingestion gets built, because the wrong format means the whole system fails silently.\
\
The result of that elicitation \'97 maybe three hours across two conversations \'97 is a much sharper specification than either the original 11+6 list or the research report. You'd end up with something like:\
\
Her top five signal sources, ranked by the historic placements they would have surfaced 30 days earlier.\
Her top three loss patterns, which tell you what competitive edge to optimise for.\
Her 50-name interim bench, which scopes the interim pillar precisely.\
Her 20-30 key account watchlist, with the specific hiring managers and warm-intro paths for each.\
Her segmented lapsed-100, with action triggers per segment.\
Her judgement taxonomy \'97 the qualitative filters she applies that no off-the-shelf tool captures.\
Her delivery format that she will actually read daily for a year.\
\
From those seven artefacts, the "critical tools" list more or less writes itself, and it will look different from both the original plan and the research report. My guess \'97 and it is a guess until the elicitation happens \'97 is that the final list is probably six tools, not eleven, because three pairs in the original plan collapse into single orchestrated systems once you're building around Sara's actual workflow rather than a conceptual taxonomy.\
The reason I'm pushing back on writing the final tool list right now is that doing it without the elicitation would repeat the original sin of the whole exercise: generating a plausible-sounding plan from first principles rather than from the ground truth of how Sara actually earns \'a314,300 at a time. The first version of anything you build should be trained on her last 20 placements and her last 30 losses, not on a signal taxonomy I or anyone else invented.\
