\fs26 \cf7 \cb5 Every signal, every orchestrator rule, every surface, every guardrail is causal to either more placements or higher fees per placement.\'a0Nothing is in this spec for any other reason.\cb1 \
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0
\cf2 \cb3 not sure this tool will deliver sufficient financial commission. This is tight. The spec has done the hard work of collapsing the original 11+6 tool list into a single orchestrated engine with four surfaces, which is the right architectural move. A few observations \'97 some structural, some where I'd push back, and one meaningful gap.\
\
**What this got right that the earlier versions didn't**\
\
The move from "tools" to "one engine with four surfaces" is the single most important change. The original plan's weakness was that each tool implied its own build, its own data store, its own ranking. Collapsing to one ingestion layer feeding one orchestrator feeding four differentiated outputs (alert, brief, on-demand, feedback) means the cross-cutting logic \'97 signal stacking, incumbent-to-candidate flip, referral-chain tracking \'97 actually works, because all signals share memory. That architectural choice is load-bearing and the spec makes it cleanly.\
\
The four surfaces are also correctly scoped to the four moments when commission is actually won. Real-time alerts win speed races. The morning brief runs her daily rhythm. The slash commands fire at the commercial truth moments \'97 retained pitch, fee negotiation, shortlist pressure \'97 where the fee multiplier is largest. The feedback loop is the only way the ranker ever becomes Sara-specific rather than generic. Nothing here is decorative.\
\
The compliance perimeter being explicit upfront is right. Without it the tool is legally fragile and can't be scaled across VMA later.\
\
**Where I'd push back**\
\
The \'a3160-240k yield projection. I gave you that number two turns ago and I'd now temper it. The Total Jobs and KPMG/REC data from the last few weeks shows permanent placements falling for over a year, candidate availability up for 37 months, and services employment contracting for 16 months straight. Even with the tool working perfectly, Sara is running into a market headwind that cuts her baseline. The honest year-one range is probably \'a390-180k of additional GP on top of whatever her FY27 baseline turns out to be, which is itself likely to undershoot her \'a3400k target. The spec should state this honestly rather than advertising the upper end. The case for building it doesn't need inflated numbers \'97 even \'a390k of uplift is a 15-20x return on tool cost, which is already overwhelming.\
\
The feedback loop as currently described is too thin. "Reply gold/junk/used/already placed/low fee/wrong seniority" is a six-label taxonomy that looks rigorous but doesn't capture the most important outcome signal: **did this lead eventually turn into a fee, and if so, how long did it take and what size?** Without that, the ranker learns to surface things Sara finds interesting, not things that paid. The loop needs to reach into JobAdder and pull the eventual outcome of each flagged lead, closing the loop on cash rather than on her first-look intuition. This is the single most important feature for year-two performance and it's under-specified here.\
\
The slash commands are listed as equal but they're not. 
\f4\fs24 \cb8 /shortlist [JD]
\f0\fs26 \cb3  and 
\f4\fs24 \cb8 /pitch-pack [account]
\f0\fs26 \cb3  are the two that move the needle most, because they operate at the moments where fees are either multiplied (retained conversion) or briefs are either won or lost (speed of response). 
\f4\fs24 \cb8 /fee-brief
\f0\fs26 \cb3  and 
\f4\fs24 \cb8 /enrich
\f0\fs26 \cb3  are useful but operate at lower-fee-multiplier moments. If build order ever matters \'97 and it will, even without explicit phasing \'97 the spec should signal this hierarchy rather than treating all four as peers.\
\
The Companies House Streaming filter is specified as CEO/CHRO/CPO/MD only. This undercounts. Worth adding: Chief People Officer (increasingly the title replacing CHRO at FTSE 350 level), Chief Communications Officer (when filed as an officer, which happens at roughly a third of large UK PLCs), and Chief Corporate Affairs Officer. Also worth including PSC changes (people with significant control) at private companies, because PE-backed portfolio companies often bring new comms needs when ownership structures shift \'97 and PE activity is one of the few areas of the UK market still growing in 2026.\
\
The 100 lapsed contacts and 25 key accounts are treated as static inputs. They shouldn't be. Sara's key account list a year from now will look different from today's, and the orchestrator should surface candidates for promotion onto and demotion from those lists based on signal density and placement history. Otherwise the watchlists go stale and the auto-promotion logic gradually becomes less useful.\
\
**The meaningful gap**\
\
The spec has no mechanism for **capturing Sara's qualitative judgement** \'97 the thing I flagged as the actual moat in my last message. The feedback loop captures binary outcomes (gold/junk). What it doesn't capture is the reasoning: *why* was this lead gold, *why* was this candidate wrong for this role, *what was it about this brief that made it retained-convertible when superficially similar ones weren't.* Without that, the tool learns her preferences but not her judgement, and her judgement is the thing a \'a3400k-target specialist recruiter is actually paid for.\
\
The fix is a lightweight "voice note or one-line rationale" mechanic attached to each feedback action. Not required, but prompted. Over twelve months this builds into a proprietary dataset of Sara's decision logic that no competitor can replicate, and which eventually makes the ranker genuinely her rather than generic. This is the piece that makes the tool defensible as an asset, not just useful as a workflow.\
\
**The other gap, smaller but worth naming**\
\
There's no specification for what happens when the tool is wrong in a visible way \'97 a signal stack that looks high-confidence but turns out to be a red herring (e.g., the CEO change was a pre-arranged succession, the HR1 filing was for a different division, the Staffbase customer was the company's previous Head of IC doing her final project before departure). Without a deliberate "false positive review" rhythm \'97 probably weekly \'97 the ranker doesn't learn from its confident mistakes, only from its conservative ones. This can be as simple as the Friday brief including a "last week's confident calls that didn't play out, and why" section. Five minutes of Sara's time, material improvement in precision over six months.\
\
**The structural point**\
\
Everything in the spec is causal to either more placements or higher fees, which is the right test. But the spec reads as finished, which no v1 tool ever is. What it doesn't have \'97 and arguably should \'97 is a stated theory of how the engine evolves, because the most important thing about it is that it gets better with use, and that property needs to be deliberately engineered rather than assumed. The feedback loop, the watchlist dynamics, the false-positive review, the qualitative-judgement capture, the outcome integration with JobAdder \'97 these are the five mechanisms that turn a useful daily brief into a compounding asset over 18 months.\
\
That framing also changes how you talk to Sara about it. This isn't a tool that delivers \'a3160-240k in year one. It's a tool that delivers maybe \'a390-140k in year one, \'a3150-220k in year two as the ranker calibrates, and \'a3200-300k+ in year three as the referral chain compounds and her desk is visibly running on richer intelligence than any rival's. The yield curve matters because it tells you what to protect \'97 the feedback mechanisms \'97 when you're inevitably tempted to drop them to ship faster.\
\
One thing to decide before you commit the spec to the branch: whether this is Sara's tool or VMA's tool. The compliance perimeter and the referral-chain logic both become more valuable if the architecture supports being extended to other VMA consultants later without having to rebuild the reasoning layer. That's a 10-15% up-front architecture cost for a potentially large downstream asset. Worth asking now rather than later.\
\
If you want, I can mark up the spec itself with these edits inline rather than leaving them as commentary.\cb1 \
