\cf2 \cb3 what do you think of this response to that: This is better in every way that matters. It's a real v1 now \'97 not a blueprint. A few observations, ordered by how much they'd change my view of shipping this as-is.\
\
**The biggest thing this version gets right**\
\
The kill-switch is the discipline the whole exercise was missing. Everything before this was "build the thing and it'll pay off" \'97 which is indistinguishable from every internal tool that gets started and abandoned. A 60-day success test with four named outcomes, any one of which clears the bar, is tight enough to force real engagement from Sara and honest enough to fail visibly if the thing doesn't work. \'a315-50k floor in 60 days is also calibrated right: large enough to matter (one interim placement at \'a315k GP clears it), small enough to be achievable on luck alone if the tool happens to fire on the right week. Good test design means the floor is plausible-but-not-guaranteed, and this threads that needle.\
\
Dropping HR1 for v1 is the right call for the stated reason (FOI response window kills it as a month-one signal), but worth flagging: HR1 is probably the single most valuable signal once the pipeline is running, because the FOI pattern means you get 4-6 weeks head start on every competitor. Drop it from v1, but make sure it's first in the queue when v2 is scoped. Otherwise the thing that eventually becomes the tool's most defensible advantage gets forgotten.\
\
Dropping the referral-chain compounding layer is correct for v1 but painful, because it's the mechanism that makes year two and three significantly larger than year one. Same logic as HR1 \'97 just note it's deferred, not killed.\
\
**Where the test might be too generous or too tight**\
\
The four outcomes are OR-gated, meaning any one clears the bar. Look again at them:\
\
1. One retained conversion via 
\f4\fs24 \cb8 /pitch-pack
\f0\fs26 \cb3  \'97 \'a320-30k fee. Rare event; if this fires, the tool is already enormously valuable. Correctly included.\
2. One or two briefs won via 
\f4\fs24 \cb8 /shortlist
\f0\fs26 \cb3  \'97 speed-race wins. Measurable but requires Sara to know she'd have lost on speed, which is a counterfactual she'll have to estimate honestly.\
3. One interim placement from the contract-end cross-reference \'97 \'a310-20k GP. Cleanly attributable.\
4. Two to four first-call-race wins leading to at least one brief \'97 the weakest gate, because "brief in her pipeline" is not cash, and the attribution chain from alert 
\f3 \uc0\u8594 
\f0  call 
\f3 \uc0\u8594 
\f0  brief 
\f3 \uc0\u8594 
\f0  placement is long and easily contaminated by other work.\
\
The gate that's soft is the fourth. A "brief in her pipeline" at day 60 is not revenue; it's activity. If you want the test to be genuinely honest, I'd either raise that bar to "brief signed, even if not yet placed" or weight the four outcomes so that (4) alone doesn't carry the decision. Otherwise there's a version of month two where Sara has two briefs in pipeline that look promising and the tool survives on the strength of activity that never converts. I'd rather the tool die on an honest zero at day 60 and get rebuilt, than limp into month three on the back of maybes.\
\
**The read-only JobAdder cross-reference is doing heavy lifting**\
\
The spec says "JobAdder read-only cross-reference \'97 her history contextualises every signal." That's a lot of work hidden behind one line. Pulling it off cleanly in month one requires the JobAdder data to be structured enough that Claude can actually match external entities (company names, contact names) to internal records reliably. In practice, JobAdder CRMs are messy \'97 same company under three different spellings, contacts without standardised job titles, historical placements not tagged consistently. If the read-only cross-reference mostly misses because of data quality, the orchestrator's most distinctive rule doesn't fire, and the tool degrades to a generic BD scraper.\
\
The practical response is to include a one-day data-hygiene pass on Sara's JobAdder before go-live. Normalise the company names for the 25 key accounts and 100 lapsed contacts (the entities the cross-reference most needs to match against), tag past placements consistently, make sure decision-maker contact records have current titles. That's 4-6 hours of Sara's time and it protects the feature that most differentiates the tool from an off-the-shelf sourcing product.\
\
**The compliance bit**\
\
LIA + DPIA + Article 14 disclosure on VMA's website "before any candidate signal is pulled" is correct and non-negotiable. But Article 14 disclosure on **VMA's** website is a corporate decision, not Sara's. If VMA's data protection officer hasn't been looped in, the disclosure doesn't exist and the tool can't legally run. This needs naming as an explicit pre-go-live gate owned by someone at VMA, not as a checkbox in the spec. Without that, you hit week two and find the whole engine paused waiting for a comms approval that no one has been tasked with driving.\
\
**One thing to add to the go-live inputs from Sara**\
\
The spec lists six things she provides before go-live. I'd add a seventh: **the 30 most recent briefs she has lost or failed to win, with who won them and why** \'97 even approximate. This is the dataset that the ranker most needs to calibrate against on day one, because it's the closest proxy for "what should I have known about, and in what timeframe, that would have changed the outcome." Without it, the first month of ranking is cold-start generic; with it, the ranker has ground truth against which to test its first hundred alerts.\
\
Four hours of Sara's time, produces the calibration set that makes the difference between the 60-day test being a noisy coin flip and a real signal.\
\
**A small one on the slash commands**\
\
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0

\f4\fs24 \cf2 \cb8 /shortlist [JD]
\f0\fs26 \cb3  and 
\f4\fs24 \cb8 /pitch-pack [account]
\f0\fs26 \cb3  are correctly Tier A. But 
\f4\fs24 \cb8 /shortlist
\f0\fs26 \cb3  is the one that gets tested hardest in the first 60 days because it fires every time Sara gets a live brief \'97 multiple times a week. If it performs badly in the first two or three live briefs, she stops using it, and a dead 
\f4\fs24 \cb8 /shortlist
\f0\fs26 \cb3  command takes the rest of the tool's credibility with it. The implication is that 
\f4\fs24 \cb8 /shortlist
\f0\fs26 \cb3  needs to be **very good** at day one, which means spending more build time on it than the minimum needed to function. Not "ship it and iterate" \'97 "ship it strong or don't ship it." The first time Sara paste a JD into it and gets five generic-feeling candidates back, the tool is dead regardless of what the other surfaces do.\
\
**The honest final read**\
\
You've gone from a sprawling 17-item plan to a v1 with a kill date and a cash test. That's a better artefact than 90% of the internal tool specs that actually get built, because most specs never get their kill dates. If the JobAdder cross-reference is clean, the 
\f4\fs24 \cb8 /shortlist
\f0\fs26 \cb3  command is strong at day one, the Article 14 disclosure is driven by someone at VMA before go-live, and the fourth success gate gets tightened from "brief in pipeline" to "brief signed" \'97 then this is shippable, and on the research's realistic yield estimates it clears the \'a315-50k floor with decent probability.\
\
Below that probability, you kill it, which is the point.\
\
One genuine caution worth naming, since you've stripped everything else: the emotional dynamic of a kill-switch is harder than the analytical one. At day 55, with two soft briefs in pipeline and no closed placements, there will be strong pressure \'97 from Sara, from you, from whoever else is invested \'97 to extend the window "just two more weeks." The spec needs someone named who will enforce the test honestly. If that's you, fine; if it's Sara, less fine, because she's the one with the career incentive to see it survive. Naming the judge now is part of the test design, not part of the rollout.\
\
That's it. Ship it when those four things are squared.\cb1 \
