\cf2 \cb3 thoughts on the below: This is shippable. The warm shutdown on kill is the move that makes this feel like a mature spec rather than a one-shot bet \'97 because it means even a failed v1 leaves VMA with four assets worth keeping (the compliance paperwork, the hygiene-passed JobAdder, the lost/won calibration set, and the signal logs), any of which could seed a v2 or a different tool entirely. That single bullet reframes the 60 days from gamble to structured experiment.\
\
Three things I'd still test before you call it done.\
\
**The sequencing of the first two weeks isn't specified, and that's where most of these tools die.** The spec tells you what runs when it's running, and how you'll know if it worked, but not how you get from signed spec to first live brief in Sara's inbox. A realistic first fortnight looks something like: week one is compliance paperwork (LIA, DPIA, Article 14 driven by the named VMA owner) and data prep (Sara's seven inputs, JobAdder hygiene pass, calibration set ingestion); week two is building and testing the five ingestion agents in parallel against the last 90 days of public data, so you can see whether the signals they produce actually match the lost briefs in Sara's calibration set. If they don't, you know before go-live that the ranker is cold-starting on the wrong signals, and you adjust. If they do, you have a real confidence signal going into day one. Without that week-two backtest, the tool ships blind and the 60-day clock is the first time you find out whether the ingestion is calibrated. That's a week of wasted runway.\
\
**The kill-switch judge needs a stated decision rubric, not just a name.** "Senior VMA figure, outside Sara's direct line, commercial view, no emotional stake" is the right person profile. But at day 60 the judge will be looking at: one retained pitch that almost landed, two briefs won where Sara thinks 
\f4\fs24 \cb8 /shortlist
\f0\fs26 \cb3  helped but can't prove it, an interim placement that's 90% closed but awaiting signature, and four signed briefs of varying fee quality in pipeline. Does the tool live or die? Without a rubric, the judge defaults to vibes, and vibes lean toward extension because everyone in the room wants it to work. The rubric doesn't need to be complicated \'97 "at least one outcome crosses its threshold cleanly and without contested attribution, or we kill" is enough. But it needs to exist before day one, not get invented at day 60.\
\
**The 
\f4\fs24 \cb8 /shortlist
\f0\fs26 \cb3  day-one quality bar is the single biggest shipping risk and the spec doesn't address how you'll hit it.** Tier A "build first, ship strong" is the right instruction but it's not a plan. In practice, 
