\f0\fs26 \cf7 \cb5 Pushback 1: source 5 isn't measured against the same calibration set.\cb1 \
\cb5 Sources 1\'964 are demand-side \'97 they predict briefs. They match against Sara's 50 event-level brief outcomes. That's clean.\cb1 \
\cb5 Source 5 (Bright Data licensed candidate signals) is supply-side \'97 it predicts candidate availability. You can't measure "did Bright Data predict the lost brief at Barclays" because Bright Data tracks candidates, not companies. Its calibration target is different:\'a0did this source show openness signals on the candidates Sara actually placed, preceding those placements?\'a0A separate threshold is needed \'97 something like "\uc0\u8805 10 openness signals matching candidates Sara placed or seriously considered in the last 12 months, across the 90-day backtest."\cb1 \
\cb5 The critique applies one rule to five sources when the sources have structurally different targets. That's a real gap.\cb1 \
\cb5 Pushback 2: hit-count alone passes noise factories.\cb1 \
\cb5 3/50 matches is fine if the source fires 100 alerts. It's useless if the source fires 10,000 alerts and 3 happen to coincide with events. Pure hit-count ignores precision.\cb1 \
\cb5 Alongside the hit-count threshold, each source needs a\'a0signal-to-noise floor\'a0\'97 e.g., at least 1 match per 20 alerts (5% precision). Measurement cost is near-zero: you're already logging all alerts and already matching against calibration set; the ratio is just those two numbers divided. Without it, a high-volume noisy source passes the threshold and then drowns Sara in garbage once live.\cb1 \
